One of my favorite things about Karma was how well he posed for photos. If you said the word “walk” he’d do this cute little head turn, look you straight in the eyes, and smile like he was a human. He was always so happy, and even right up to the last days, had the energy for a another trip around the block or chasing squirrels in the park. 

Before he passed, I was asked to write an article on Vocal about how we kept him so active and strong, and we took some photos together in the kitchen that I’ll keep forever. You can check out the article and photos with the link in my bio. #ad @vocal_creators @ollie

When I was 6 years old, I went to go live with my Gram in Idaho. She had a house on a piece of property where she taught me how to save money, grow my own garden, and raise chickens for meat. When she noticed my love for singing and music, she encouraged me by signing me up for voice lessons and local choir groups. She believed in me before anyone else did, and I wouldn’t have made it to where I am today without the sacrifices she made for me. 

Recently, I got to sit down with some new friends of mine and write a song that pays tribute to the impact she’s had on my life. I’m so grateful to @marykutter and @chrissligh for helping me bring this project to life and for giving me such a warm welcome to Nashville that day. I’m excited to write more and get back into the swing of things!

I don’t know about y’all, but my mom taught me how to work! For years, she worked the graveyard shift waiting tables at a little country cafe and for a lot of those years I was working alongside her bussing those tables. Around 2am, the bar crowd would come pouring in and fill that place and Mom would be running circles around those tables taking care of everyone— all while singing at her top of her lungs to the music on the jukebox. She knew everyone by name and she knew everyone’s business. She made sure people would get home safely, and she didn’t put up with any crap from drunk guys. Sometimes, she was even a shoulder to cry on for some of the girls out front. When our shift was over, she’d change the till and have me count her tips. Most nights she was making over a couple hundred bucks just in tips!! That’s when I realized the people weren’t coming in just for scones and eggs after a night of partying, they were coming in to see my mom and she loved them all the same! Working in that diner was some of the best years of my life, I’ll never forget it. I hope everyone has a great Mother’s Day weekend! Love you momma!

I’ve been seeing this certain quote everywhere lately so I wanted to share it with you.
. 
“It won’t happen overnight, but if you give up it won’t happen at all!”
.
Ain’t that THE TRUTH ‼️
.
Thank you to anyone whose ever supported my music in any capacity—whether it’s by streaming, downloading, sharing, or even showing up to a show. We’ve had a lot of ups and downs over the years and I’ve learned so much throughout it all. The songs I’ve written just in the last 6 months are hands down the best material I’ve ever worked on and I’m so excited for you to hear them.
.
But that’s not what keeps me going. There have been countless times where I’ve felt defeated or felt like giving up—but it’s in those moments I remember that music isn’t just something I do, it’s who I am. 
.
Here’s to never giving up who I am! 🙌 Thanks for being along for the ride!
